{"title_page": "Mary Gaitskill", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Mary Gaitskill\n| image = Mary Gaitskill BBF 2010 Shankbone.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Gaitskill at the 2010 [[Brooklyn Book Festival]]\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Lexington, Kentucky]], United States\n| alma_mater = [[University of Michigan]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = writer\n| nationality = American\n| period = 1980s-present\n| genre = literary short story, novel, essay, Transgressive Fiction\n| subject = \n| movement = \n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Mary Gaitskill''' (born November 11, 1954) is an American novelist, essayist, and short story writer. Her work has appeared in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''The Best American Short Stories'' (1993, 2006, 2012), and ''The O. Henry Prize Stories'' (1998, 2008).\n\n==Life==\nGaitskill was born in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. She has lived in [[New York City]], [[Toronto]], [[San Francisco]], [[Marin County, California|Marin County]] and [[Pennsylvania]], as well as attending the [[University of Michigan]], where she earned her B.A. in 1981<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blueflowerarts.com/artist/mary-gaitskill/|title=Mary Gaitskill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> and won a [[Hopwood Award]]. She sold flowers in San Francisco as a teenage runaway. In a conversation with novelist and short story writer [[Matthew Sharpe]] for ''[[BOMB Magazine]]'', Gaitskill said she chose to become a writer at age 18 because she was \"indignant about things\u2014it was the typical teenage sense of 'things are wrong in the world and I must say something.'\"<ref>Sharpe, Matthew. [http://bombsite.com/issues/107/articles/3265 \"Mary Gaitskill\"]. ''[[BOMB Magazine]]''. Spring 2009. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref> Gaitskill has also recounted (in her essay \"Revelation\") becoming a born-again Christian at age 21 but lapsing after six months.\n\nShe married the writer [[Peter Trachtenberg]] in 2001. They divorced in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrodale|first=Amie|title=I'm Psychic... with Mary Gaitskill|url=https://www.vice.com/read/im-psychic-mary-gaitskill|work=Interview with Vice Magazine|magazine=Vice Magazine|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill has taught at [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]], the [[University of Houston]], [[New York University]], [[The New School]], [[Brown University]], in the MFA program at [[Temple University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cla.temple.edu/english/faculty/mary-gaitskill/|title=Department of English: Mary Gaitskill|publisher=Temple University College of Liberal Arts|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162351/http://www.cla.temple.edu/english/faculty/mary-gaitskill/|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Syracuse University]]. She was the Writer-In-Residence at [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges]]. As of 2020, Gaitskill is a [[Visiting Professor|visiting professor]] of literature at [[Claremont McKenna College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmc.edu/news/prof-mary-gaitskill-recognized-by-american-academy-of-arts-and-letters|title=Prof. Mary Gaitskill recognized by American Academy of Arts and Letters|last=Affairs|first=Office of Public|last2=Claremont|first2=Communications 400 N. Claremont Blvd|website=cmc.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04|last3=537-3559}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nGaitskill attempted to find a publisher for four years before her first book, the short story collection ''Bad Behavior,'' was published in 1988. The first four stories are written in the third person point of view from the perspectives of male characters. The remaining five stories are written from the perspectives of female characters. ''Secretary'' is the only story in the book written in the first person point of view. Several of the stories have themes of sexuality, romance, love, [[sex work]], [[sadomasochism]], drug addiction, being a writer in New York City, and living in New York City. ''A Romantic Weekend'' and ''Secretary'' both explore themes of [[BDSM]] and psychological aspects of dominance and submission in sexual relationships. The story ''Connection'' is about a female friendship.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=Bad Behavior|date=1988|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4391-4887-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/badbehaviorstori0000gait}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill's fiction is typically about female characters dealing with their own inner conflicts, and her subject matter matter-of-factly includes many \"taboo\" subjects such as [[prostitution]], [[Substance dependence|addiction]], and [[sado-masochism]].  Gaitskill says that she had worked as a stripper and call girl.  She showed similar candor in an essay about being raped, \"On Not Being a Victim,\" for ''[[Harper's]]''.\n\nGaitskill's 1994 essay in ''Harper's'' also addresses feminist debates about [[date rape]], victimization, and responsibility. She describes ways that individual subjectivity influences all experiences, making it impossible to come to \"universally agreed-upon conclusions.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=On Not Being a Victim|journal=Harper's Magazine|date=March 1994|volume=288|issue=1726|page=35}}</ref>\n\nThe film ''[[Secretary (2002 film)|Secretary]]'' (2002) is based on the short story of the same name in ''Bad Behavior'', although the two have little in common.  She characterized the film as \"the ''[[Pretty Woman]]'' version, heavy on the charm (and a little too nice),\" but observed that the \"bottom line is that if [a film adaptation is] made you get some money and exposure, and people can make up their minds from there.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mary Gaitskill Interview|url=http://failbetter.com/19/GaitskillInterview.php?sxnSrc=ltst|publisher=Failbetter|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe novel ''Two Girls, Fat and Thin'' follows the childhood and adult lives of Justine Shade (thin) and Dorothy Never (fat).  Justine works through her sadomasochistic issues while Dorothy works through her up-and-down commitment to the philosophy of \"Definitism\" and its founder \"Anna Granite\" (thinly veiled satires of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]] and [[Ayn Rand]]).  When journalist Justine interviews Dorothy for an expos\u00e9 of Definitism, an unusual relationship begins between the two women.  In an interview, Gaitskill discussed what she was trying to convey about Justine via her sadomasochistic impulses:\n\n{{ quote|It's a kind of inward aggression. It seems like self-contempt, but it's really an inverted contempt for everything. That's what I was trying to describe in her. I would say it had to do with her childhood, not because she was sexually abused, but because the world that she was presented with was so inadequate in terms of giving her a full-spirited sense of herself. That inadequacy can make you implode with a lot of disgust. It can become the gestalt of who you are. So the masochism is like \"I'm going to make myself into a debased object because that is what I think of you. This is what I think of your love. I don't want your love. Your love is shit. Your love is nothing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Alexander Laurence (originally at Altx.com) |url=http://www.altx.com/int2/mary.gaitskill.html |date=1994 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921215639/http://www.altx.com/int2/mary.gaitskill.html |archivedate=2016-09-21 }}</ref>}}\n\nThe novel ''The Mare'', published in 2015, is written from the perspectives of several different characters. The primary characters are named Ginger and Velvet (short for Velveteen). Ginger is a middle-aged woman who meets Velvet, a young adolescent, through [[The Fresh Air Fund]]. Other characters whose perspectives are featured include Paul (Ginger's husband), Silvia (Velvet's mother), Dante (Velvet's younger brother), and Beverly (a horse trainer).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=The Mare|date=2015|publisher=Pantheon|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-37974-0}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill's honors include a Guggenheim Fellowship in 2002 and a PEN/Faulkner Award nomination for ''Because They Wanted To'' in 1998. ''Veronica'' (2005) was a [[National Book Award]] nominee, as well as a National Book Critics Circle finalist for that year.  The book is centered on the narrator, a former fashion model and her friend Veronica who contracts [[AIDS]].  Gaitskill mentioned working on the novel in a 1994 interview, but that same year she put it aside until 2001.  Writing of ''Veronica'' and Gaitskill's career in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'' in March 2006, [[Wyatt Mason]] said:\n\n{{ quote|Through four books over eighteen years, Mary Gaitskill has been formulating her fiction around the immutable question of how we manage to live in a seemingly inscrutable world. In the past, she has described, with clarity and vision, the places in life where we sometimes get painfully caught. Until ''Veronica'', however, she had never ventured to show fully how life could also be made a place where, despite all, we find meaningful release.}}\n\nGaitskill's favorite writers have changed over time, as she noted in a 2005 interview,<ref>[http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?z=y&cid=973021#interview Barnes & Noble.com - Mary Gaitskill - Books: Meet the Writers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> but one constant is the author [[Vladimir Nabokov]], whose ''[[Lolita]]'' \"will be on my ten favorites list until the end of my life.\" Another consistently named influence is [[Flannery O'Connor]]. Despite her well-known S/M themes, Gaitskill does not appear to consider the [[Marquis de Sade]] himself an influence, or at least not a literary one:  \"I don't think much of Sade as a writer, although I enjoyed beating off to him as a child.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Alexander Laurence/Portable Infinite (originally at Altx.com)|url=http://portable-infinite.blogspot.com/2006/11/mary-gaitskill-interview.html|date=1994}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Bad Behavior'' (1988) (stories) {{ISBN|0-671-65871-9}}\n*''Two Girls, Fat and Thin'' (1991) (novel) {{ISBN|0-671-68540-6}}\n*''Because They Wanted To'' (1997) (stories) {{ISBN|0-684-80856-0}}\n*''Veronica'' (2005) (novel, [[National Book Award]] Finalist) {{ISBN|0-375-42145-9}}\n*''Don't Cry'' (2009) (stories) {{ISBN|0-375-42419-9}}\n*''The Mare'' (November 2015) (novel) {{ISBN|978-0307379740}}\n*''Somebody with a Little Hammer'' (2017) (essays) {{ISBN|0-307-37822-5}}\n\n==Awards==\n\n* [[Hopwood Award]]\n* [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] for fiction (2002)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriters.as.uky.edu/presenters/mary-gaitskill|title=Mary Gaitskill {{!}} womenwriters.as.uky.edu|website=womenwriters.as.uky.edu|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n* Cullman Research Fellowship at the [[New York Public Library]] (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriters.as.uky.edu/presenters/mary-gaitskill|title=Mary Gaitskill {{!}} womenwriters.as.uky.edu|website=womenwriters.as.uky.edu|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n* Arts and Letters Award in Literature, [[The American Academy of Arts and Letters]] (2018).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.narrativemagazine.com/issues/spring-2010/mary-gaitskill Author interview] (2010) by Suzanne Warren at [http://www.narrativemagazine.com/issues/spring-2010/mary-gaitskill Narrative.com].\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.collegecrier.com/interviews/int-00351.asp |work=College Crier |first=Carri Anne |last=Yager |title=Mary Gaitskill: Critics line up to praise her work- and don't have a clue |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009042111/http://www.collegecrier.com/interviews/int-00351.asp |archivedate=2007-10-09 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060421140536/http://www.failbetter.com/19/GaitskillInterview.htm Author interview] (2005?) at [http://www.failbetter.com failbetter.com].\n* [http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?z=y&cid=973021#interview Author interview] (2005) for Barnes & Noble's \"Meet the Writers\" website.  Includes lists of her current favorites in fiction and film.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060515190940/http://newyorkmetro.com/nymetro/arts/books/14988/index.html Article] (\"Mary, Mary, Less Contrary\" by Emily Nussbaum) in ''New York Magazine'' (November 14, 2005 issue).\n*The March 2006 ''Harper's'' had a notable review (not online, it appears) of ''Veronica'' by Wyatt Mason that also covered Gaitskill's earlier work.  At [http://www.slate.com/id/2133842/ Slate.com], Mason called ''Veronica'' \"the best book of fiction in recent memory.\"\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070204114715/http://bookishlove.net/?p=6 2006 Reading report, Gaitskill with Edna O'Brien at 92nd Street Y] from BookishLove.net\n* [http://believermag.com/issues/200902/?read=interview_gaitskill Author interview] (2009) with Sheila Heti at The Believer.\n* [http://bombsite.com/issues/107/articles/3265 2009 ''BOMB Magazine'' interview of Mary Gaitskill by Matthew Sharpe]\n*[http://fictionwritersreview.com/interview/woman-to-woman-an-interview-with-mary-gaitskill/ \"Woman to Woman: An Interview with Mary Gaitskill\"] (2011)  by Emily McLaughlin at Fiction Writers Review.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaitskill, Mary}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Lexington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:MacDowell Colony fellows]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:BDSM writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hopwood Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Mary Gaitskill\n| image = Mary Gaitskill BBF 2010 Shankbone.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Gaitskill at the 2010 [[Brooklyn Book Festival]]\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Lexington, Kentucky]], United States\n| alma_mater = [[University of Michigan]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = writer\n| nationality = American\n| period = 1980s-present\n| genre = literary short story, novel, essay, Transgressive Fiction\n| subject = \n| movement = \n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Mary Gaitskill''' (born November 11, 1954) is an American novelist, essayist, and short story writer. Her work has appeared in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''The Best American Short Stories'' (1993, 2006, 2012), and ''The O. Henry Prize Stories'' (1998, 2008).\n\n==Life==\nGaitskill was born in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. She has lived in [[New York City]], [[Toronto]], [[San Francisco]], [[Marin County, California|Marin County]] and [[Pennsylvania]], as well as attending the [[University of Michigan]], where she earned her B.A. in 1981<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blueflowerarts.com/artist/mary-gaitskill/|title=Mary Gaitskill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> and won a [[Hopwood Award]]. She sold flowers in San Francisco as a teenage runaway. In a conversation with novelist and short story writer [[Matthew Sharpe]] for ''[[BOMB Magazine]]'', Gaitskill said she chose to become a writer at age 18 because she was \"indignant about things\u2014it was the typical teenage sense of 'things are wrong in the world and I must say something.'\"<ref>Sharpe, Matthew. [http://bombsite.com/issues/107/articles/3265 \"Mary Gaitskill\"]. ''[[BOMB Magazine]]''. Spring 2009. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref> Gaitskill has also recounted (in her essay \"Revelation\") becoming a born-again Christian at age 21 but lapsing after six months.\n\nShe married the writer [[Peter Trachtenberg]] in 2001. They divorced in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrodale|first=Amie|title=I'm Psychic... with Mary Gaitskill|url=https://www.vice.com/read/im-psychic-mary-gaitskill|work=Interview with Vice Magazine|magazine=Vice Magazine|accessdate=October 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill has taught at [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]], the [[University of Houston]], [[New York University]], [[The New School]], [[Brown University]], in the MFA program at [[Temple University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cla.temple.edu/english/faculty/mary-gaitskill/|title=Department of English: Mary Gaitskill|publisher=Temple University College of Liberal Arts|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162351/http://www.cla.temple.edu/english/faculty/mary-gaitskill/|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Syracuse University]]. She was the Writer-In-Residence at [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges]]. As of 2020, Gaitskill is a [[Visiting Professor|visiting professor]] of literature at [[Claremont McKenna College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmc.edu/news/prof-mary-gaitskill-recognized-by-american-academy-of-arts-and-letters|title=Prof. Mary Gaitskill recognized by American Academy of Arts and Letters|last=Affairs|first=Office of Public|last2=Claremont|first2=Communications 400 N. Claremont Blvd|website=cmc.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04|last3=537-3559}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nGaitskill attempted to find a publisher for four years before her first book, the short story collection ''Bad Behavior,'' was published in 1988. The first four stories are written in the third person point of view from the perspectives of male characters. The remaining five stories are written from the perspectives of female characters. ''Secretary'' is the only story in the book written in the first person point of view. Several of the stories have themes of sexuality, romance, love, [[sex work]], [[sadomasochism]], drug addiction, being a writer in New York City, and living in New York City. ''A Romantic Weekend'' and ''Secretary'' both explore themes of [[BDSM]] and psychological aspects of dominance and submission in sexual relationships. The story ''Connection'' is about a female friendship.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=Bad Behavior|date=1988|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4391-4887-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/badbehaviorstori0000gait}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill's fiction is typically about female characters dealing with their own inner conflicts, and her subject matter matter-of-factly includes many \"taboo\" subjects such as [[prostitution]], [[Substance dependence|addiction]], and [[sado-masochism]].  Gaitskill says that she had worked as a stripper and call girl.  She showed similar candor in an essay about being raped, \"On Not Being a Victim,\" for ''[[Harper's]]''.\n\nGaitskill's 1994 essay in ''Harper's'' also addresses feminist debates about [[date rape]], victimization, and responsibility. She describes ways that individual subjectivity influences all experiences, making it impossible to come to \"universally agreed-upon conclusions.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=On Not Being a Victim|journal=Harper's Magazine|date=March 1994|volume=288|issue=1726|page=35}}</ref>\n\nThe film ''[[Secretary (2002 film)|Secretary]]'' (2002) is based on the short story of the same name in ''Bad Behavior'', although the two have little in common.  She characterized the film as \"the ''[[Pretty Woman]]'' version, heavy on the charm (and a little too nice),\" but observed that the \"bottom line is that if [a film adaptation is] made you get some money and exposure, and people can make up their minds from there.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mary Gaitskill Interview|url=http://failbetter.com/19/GaitskillInterview.php?sxnSrc=ltst|publisher=Failbetter|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe novel ''Two Girls, Fat and Thin'' follows the childhood and adult lives of Justine Shade (thin) and Dorothy Never (fat).  Justine works through her sadomasochistic issues while Dorothy works through her up-and-down commitment to the philosophy of \"Definitism\" and its founder \"Anna Granite\" (thinly veiled satires of [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]] and [[Ayn Rand]]).  When journalist Justine interviews Dorothy for an expos\u00e9 of Definitism, an unusual relationship begins between the two women.  In an interview, Gaitskill discussed what she was trying to convey about Justine via her sadomasochistic impulses:\n\n{{ quote|It's a kind of inward aggression. It seems like self-contempt, but it's really an inverted contempt for everything. That's what I was trying to describe in her. I would say it had to do with her childhood, not because she was sexually abused, but because the world that she was presented with was so inadequate in terms of giving her a full-spirited sense of herself. That inadequacy can make you implode with a lot of disgust. It can become the gestalt of who you are. So the masochism is like \"I'm going to make myself into a debased object because that is what I think of you. This is what I think of your love. I don't want your love. Your love is shit. Your love is nothing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Alexander Laurence (originally at Altx.com) |url=http://www.altx.com/int2/mary.gaitskill.html |date=1994 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921215639/http://www.altx.com/int2/mary.gaitskill.html |archivedate=2016-09-21 }}</ref>}}\n\nThe novel ''The Mare'', published in 2015, is written from the perspectives of several different characters. The primary characters are named Ginger and Velvet (short for Velveteen). Ginger is a middle-aged woman who meets Velvet, a young adolescent, through [[The Fresh Air Fund]]. Other characters whose perspectives are featured include Paul (Ginger's husband), Silvia (Velvet's mother), Dante (Velvet's younger brother), and Beverly (a horse trainer).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gaitskill|first1=Mary|title=The Mare|date=2015|publisher=Pantheon|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-37974-0}}</ref>\n\nGaitskill's honors include a Guggenheim Fellowship in 2002 and a PEN/Faulkner Award nomination for ''Because They Wanted To'' in 1998. ''Veronica'' (2005) was a [[National Book Award]] nominee, as well as a National Book Critics Circle finalist for that year.  The book is centered on the narrator, a former fashion model and her friend Veronica who contracts [[AIDS]].  Gaitskill mentioned working on the novel in a 1994 interview, but that same year she put it aside until 2001.  Writing of ''Veronica'' and Gaitskill's career in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'' in March 2006, [[Wyatt Mason]] said:\n\n{{ quote|Through four books over eighteen years, Mary Gaitskill has been formulating her fiction around the immutable question of how we manage to live in a seemingly inscrutable world. In the past, she has described, with clarity and vision, the places in life where we sometimes get painfully caught. Until ''Veronica'', however, she had never ventured to show fully how life could also be made a place where, despite all, we find meaningful release.}}\n\nGaitskill's favorite writers have changed over time, as she noted in a 2005 interview,<ref>[http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?z=y&cid=973021#interview Barnes & Noble.com - Mary Gaitskill - Books: Meet the Writers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> but one constant is the author [[Vladimir Nabokov]], whose ''[[Lolita]]'' \"will be on my ten favorites list until the end of my life.\" Another consistently named influence is [[Flannery O'Connor]]. Despite her well-known S/M themes, Gaitskill does not appear to consider the [[Marquis de Sade]] himself an influence, or at least not a literary one:  \"I don't think much of Sade as a writer, although I enjoyed beating off to him as a child.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Alexander Laurence/Portable Infinite (originally at Altx.com)|url=http://portable-infinite.blogspot.com/2006/11/mary-gaitskill-interview.html|date=1994}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Bad Behavior'' (1988) (stories) {{ISBN|0-671-65871-9}}\n*''Two Girls, Fat and Thin'' (1991) (novel) {{ISBN|0-671-68540-6}}\n*''Because They Wanted To'' (1997) (stories) {{ISBN|0-684-80856-0}}\n*''Veronica'' (2005) (novel, [[National Book Award]] Finalist) {{ISBN|0-375-42145-9}}\n*''Don't Cry'' (2009) (stories) {{ISBN|0-375-42419-9}}\n*''The Mare'' (November 2015) (novel) {{ISBN|978-0307379740}}\n*''Somebody with a Little Hammer'' (2017) (essays) {{ISBN|0-307-37822-5}}\n\n==Awards==\n\n* [[Hopwood Award]]\n* [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] for fiction (2002)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriters.as.uky.edu/presenters/mary-gaitskill|title=Mary Gaitskill {{!}} womenwriters.as.uky.edu|website=womenwriters.as.uky.edu|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n* Cullman Research Fellowship at the [[New York Public Library]] (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenwriters.as.uky.edu/presenters/mary-gaitskill|title=Mary Gaitskill {{!}} womenwriters.as.uky.edu|website=womenwriters.as.uky.edu|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.narrativemagazine.com/issues/spring-2010/mary-gaitskill Author interview] (2010) by Suzanne Warren at [http://www.narrativemagazine.com/issues/spring-2010/mary-gaitskill Narrative.com].\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.collegecrier.com/interviews/int-00351.asp |work=College Crier |first=Carri Anne |last=Yager |title=Mary Gaitskill: Critics line up to praise her work- and don't have a clue |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009042111/http://www.collegecrier.com/interviews/int-00351.asp |archivedate=2007-10-09 }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060421140536/http://www.failbetter.com/19/GaitskillInterview.htm Author interview] (2005?) at [http://www.failbetter.com failbetter.com].\n* [http://www.barnesandnoble.com/writers/writerdetails.asp?z=y&cid=973021#interview Author interview] (2005) for Barnes & Noble's \"Meet the Writers\" website.  Includes lists of her current favorites in fiction and film.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060515190940/http://newyorkmetro.com/nymetro/arts/books/14988/index.html Article] (\"Mary, Mary, Less Contrary\" by Emily Nussbaum) in ''New York Magazine'' (November 14, 2005 issue).\n*The March 2006 ''Harper's'' had a notable review (not online, it appears) of ''Veronica'' by Wyatt Mason that also covered Gaitskill's earlier work.  At [http://www.slate.com/id/2133842/ Slate.com], Mason called ''Veronica'' \"the best book of fiction in recent memory.\"\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070204114715/http://bookishlove.net/?p=6 2006 Reading report, Gaitskill with Edna O'Brien at 92nd Street Y] from BookishLove.net\n* [http://believermag.com/issues/200902/?read=interview_gaitskill Author interview] (2009) with Sheila Heti at The Believer.\n* [http://bombsite.com/issues/107/articles/3265 2009 ''BOMB Magazine'' interview of Mary Gaitskill by Matthew Sharpe]\n*[http://fictionwritersreview.com/interview/woman-to-woman-an-interview-with-mary-gaitskill/ \"Woman to Woman: An Interview with Mary Gaitskill\"] (2011)  by Emily McLaughlin at Fiction Writers Review.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaitskill, Mary}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Lexington, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:MacDowell Colony fellows]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:BDSM writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Hopwood Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Mthwaite", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards:Arts and Letters Award in Literature,The American Academy of Arts and Letters", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Gaitskill"}
{"title_page": "Danial Hajibarat", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Danial Hajibarat|timestamp=20200409211547|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Danial Hajibarat|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Danial Hajibarat\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =Danial-Hajibarat07.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|6|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = University College Yadegar In Tehran\n| occupation         = [[Film director]] and [[screenwriter]] , [[Filmmaker]]\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Danial Hajibarat''' ({{lang-fa| \u062f\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627\u0644 \u062d\u0627\u062c\u064a \u0628\u0631\u0627\u062a}}, {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6|j|i|b|\u00e6|r|\u00e6|t}}; June 4, 1983) is an [[Iran]]ian [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]] and also [[TV series]] [[actor]] in [[Iran]].\n\n== Biography ==\n'''Danial Hajibarat''',(born 4 June 1983) in [[Tehran]] ,Iran <ref>{{cite web|title=Biography Danial Hajibarat|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9158799|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=12 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[film director]], [[screenwriter]], and [[Film producer|producer]]. He is now a [[independent filmmaker]] in Iran.\n\nHe started his career from the early age in school theater. In 2003, he began made with [[short film]]s and [[video clip]]s and in the following years, He participated in the [[theater]]s of Ases and [[Fajr International Film Festival|Fajr]] Festival, He did a lot of work behind the scenes in movies and TV series.\n\nHe made his first independent film Inception in 2014 and In 2016 he made his first independent feature film The Road of Love  that has entered to several international film festivals.\n\nHe is also one of the champion of the Iranian car racing.\n\nHe started photography professionally since his adolescence.\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     =\n | image1    =\n | image2    =\n | image3    =\n}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Directed features and production===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Production\n|-\n| 2011 || ''In the silence of the candle off''<ref>{{cite web|title=In the silence of the|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7780248|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=24 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> || Adel Shojaei || Bidel Irania\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Hasht Behesht''<ref>{{cite web|title=Hasht Behesht TV Series|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10500488|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Saeed Alemzadeh || Afagh Film \n|-\n| 2013 || ''Kolah too Kolah''<ref>{{cite web|title=Kolah too Kolah TV Movie |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11513874|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Hadi Rahimi Khas || Namaye baz Sepahan \n|-\n| 2013 || ''Maybe There''<ref>{{cite web|title=Maybe There TV Movie|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11591834|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Milad Jarmooz ||  Namaye baz Sepahan \n|-\n| 2014 || ''Inception''<ref>{{cite web|title=Inception|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7321322|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Expectation''<ref>{{cite web|title=Expectation|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7841412|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2016 || ''You and the Whole''<ref>{{cite web|title=You and the Whole|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7179112|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[The Road of Love]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Road of Love|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7380834|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=1 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2017 || ''The Death Story of Sohrab''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death Story of Sohrab|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11555166|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=1 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ||Farshad Ahmadi Dastgerdi ||  \n|-\n| 2017 || ''It's just a cigarette''<ref>{{cite web|title=It's just a cigarette|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7741748|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2018 || ''Ability''<ref>{{cite web|title=Ability|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8221948|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=14 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania\n|-\n| 2018 || ''Founders of Isfahan college of Physics''<ref>{{cite web|title=Founders of Isfahan college of Physics|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10374294|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=2 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2018 || ''Delusion''<ref>{{cite web|title=Delusion|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt9119756|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=26 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[ Liberation (Movie) |Liberation]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberation|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10160650|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2020 || ''The Madness''<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberation|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11979934/|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|}\n\n==References==\n*{{IMDb name|9158799}}\n*[http://bidelirania.ir/2020/01/14/%D8%A8%DB%8C%D9%88%DA%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%81%DB%8C-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%AC%DB%8C-%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA/  Danial Hajibarat in the Bidel Irania Film Company]\n*[https://www.kinopoisk.ru/name/4813605/ Danial Hajibarat in the kinopoisk]\n*[https://www.aparat.com/result/danial_haji_barat/ Danial Hajibarat in the Aparat]\n*[https://7watchlist.com/Celebrities/301660/danial_hajibarat/ 7watchlis]\n*[https://filcin.com/person/81727/%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%86%DB%8C%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%AC%DB%8C-%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA Filcin]\n*[https://www.namasha.com/bidel.irania/ Namsha]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{instagram|danial_hajibarat}}\n*{{facebook|danial.hajibarat}}\n*{{twitter|DanialHajibarat}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iranian male television actors]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hajibarat, Danial}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian film directors]]\n[[Category:Iranian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:Iranian male film actors]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Danial Hajibarat|timestamp=20200409211547|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Danial Hajibarat|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Danial Hajibarat\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =Danial-Hajibarat07.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|6|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| citizenship        = \n| alma_mater         = University College Yadegar In Tehran\n| occupation         = [[Film director]] and [[screenwriter]] , [[Filmmaker]]\n| years_active       = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n\n'''Danial Hajibarat''' ({{lang-fa| \u062f\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627\u0644 \u062d\u0627\u062c\u064a \u0628\u0631\u0627\u062a}}, {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6|j|i|b|\u00e6|r|\u00e6|t}}; June 4, 1983) is an [[Iran]]ian [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]] and also [[TV series]] [[actor]] in [[Iran]].\n\n== Biography ==\n'''Danial Hajibarat''',(born 4 June 1983) in [[Tehran]] ,Iran <ref>{{cite web|title=Biography Danial Hajibarat|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9158799|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=12 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[film director]], [[screenwriter]], and [[Film producer|producer]]. He is now a [[independent filmmaker]] in Iran.\n\nHe started his career from the early age in school theater. In 2003, he began made with [[short film]]s and [[video clip]]s and in the following years, He participated in the [[theater]]s of Ases and [[Fajr International Film Festival|Fajr]] Festival, He did a lot of work behind the scenes in movies and TV series.\n\nHe made his first independent film Inception in 2014 and In 2016 he made his first independent feature film The Road of Love  that has entered to several international film festivals.\n\nHe is also one of the champion of the Iranian car racing.\n\nHe started photography professionally since his adolescence.\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     =\n | image1    =\n | image2    =\n | image3    =\n}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Directed features and production===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Production\n|-\n| 2011 || ''In the silence of the candle off''<ref>{{cite web|title=In the silence of the|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7780248|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=24 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> || Adel Shojaei || Bidel Irania\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Hasht Behesht''<ref>{{cite web|title=Hasht Behesht TV Series|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10500488|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Saeed Alemzadeh || Afagh Film \n|-\n| 2013 || ''Kolah too Kolah''<ref>{{cite web|title=Kolah too Kolah TV Movie |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11513874|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Hadi Rahimi Khas || Namaye baz Sepahan \n|-\n| 2013 || ''Maybe There''<ref>{{cite web|title=Maybe There TV Movie|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11591834|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=15 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> || Milad Jarmooz ||  Namaye baz Sepahan \n|-\n| 2014 || ''Inception''<ref>{{cite web|title=Inception|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7321322|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Expectation''<ref>{{cite web|title=Expectation|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7841412|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com/|archive-date=24 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> || Danial Hajibarat || Bidel Irania \n|-\n| 2016 || ''You and the Whole''<ref>{{cite web|title=You and the Whole|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt7179112|website=IMDb|archive-url=https://www.imdb.com