{"title_page": "Orange (Al Stewart album)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Orange\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Al Stewart]]\n| cover      = Al_orange.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1 January 1972\n| recorded   = September 1971\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Trident Studios]], [[London]]\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]], [[progressive rock]]\n| length     = 38:45\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|CBS]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA16-PA1970&lpg=RA16-PA1970&dq=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&source=bl&ots=JcrTurWiXt&sig=ACfU3U3ebMOsItk06edQeS1Yrz0FxC3pzg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjs77LR-rDmAhUBVs0KHbvUB144UBDoATACegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|first=Colin|last=Larkin|date=27 May 2011|publisher=Omnibus Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| producer   = [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]]\n| prev_title = [[Zero She Flies]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Past, Present and Future (Al Stewart album)|Past, Present and Future]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/orange-mw0000123482|title=Orange - Al Stewart &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''Orange''''' is the fourth studio album by [[Al Stewart]], originally released in 1972, and re-released in 1996 and 2007 on [[Compact Disc|CD]]. Generally regarded as a 'transitional album' between the confessional folk sounds of his first three albums and the historically themed albums of his more successful mid-1970s period, the album includes [[Rick Wakeman]] on piano as well as future [[Elvis Costello and the Attractions]] bassist [[Bruce Thomas]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Al Stewart except where noted.\n\n===Original LP release===\n#\"You Don't Even Know Me\" \u2013 4:00\n#\"Amsterdam\" \u2013 2:56\n#\"Songs Out of Clay\" \u2013 4:16\n#\"The News from Spain\" \u2013 6:34\n#\"[[I Don't Believe You (She Acts Like We Never Have Met)|I Don't Believe You]]\" ([[Bob Dylan]]) \u2013 3:38\n#\"Once an Orange, Always an Orange\" \u2013 4:18\n#\"I'm Falling\" \u2013 4:28\n#\"Night of the 4th of May\" \u2013 6:27\n\n===2007 Collector's Choice Music bonus tracks===\n* \"Soho\" \u2013 3:57\n* \"Elvaston Place\" \u2013 2:52\n* \"It Doesn't Matter Anymore\" ([[Paul Anka]]) \u2013 2:25\n\n==Personnel==\n*Al Stewart \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Tim Renwick]] \u2013 electric guitar (all tracks), Spanish guitar (3)\n*[[Rick Wakeman]] \u2013 piano, organ<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=60Jde3l7WNwC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&source=bl&ots=x7VkxtOZZi&sig=ACfU3U2Bsz5-0CEaIQLerWtddmzQ-WLR3w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLo4qQ-rDmAhWTGs0KHZZtCGA4MhDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&f=false|title=Legends of Rock Guitar: The Essential Reference of Rock's Greatest Guitarists|first1=Pete|last1=Prown|first2=Harvey P.|last2=Newquist|date=12 December 1997|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*Bruce Thomas / Brian Odgers \u2013 bass\n*Graham Hunt / Roger Pope / John Wilson \u2013 drums\n*[[Bob Andrews (keyboardist)|Bob Andrews]] \u2013 organ (8)\n*Cal Batchelor \u2013 Spanish guitar (3)\n*Tim Walker \u2013 Spanish guitar (4)\n*John Donnelly, Kevin Powers, Mick Welton \u2013 backing vocals (2)\n*[[Brinsley Schwarz (musician) |Brinsley Schwarz]] \u2013 12-string acoustic guitar\n*[[David Hentschel]] \u2013 engineer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Al Stewart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orange (Al Stewart Album)}}\n[[Category:1972 albums]]\n[[Category:Al Stewart albums]]\n[[Category:CBS Records albums]]\n[[Category:Collectors' Choice Music albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Anthony (record producer)]]\n[[Category:albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n\n{{1970s-rock-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Orange\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Al Stewart]]\n| cover      = Al_orange.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1 January 1972\n| recorded   = September 1971\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Trident Studios]], [[London]]\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]], [[progressive rock]]\n| length     = 38:45\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|CBS]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=RA16-PA1970&lpg=RA16-PA1970&dq=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&source=bl&ots=JcrTurWiXt&sig=ACfU3U3ebMOsItk06edQeS1Yrz0FxC3pzg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjs77LR-rDmAhUBVs0KHbvUB144UBDoATACegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|first=Colin|last=Larkin|date=27 May 2011|publisher=Omnibus Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| producer   = [[John Anthony (record producer)|John Anthony]]\n| prev_title = [[Zero She Flies]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = [[Past, Present and Future (Al Stewart album)|Past, Present and Future]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/orange-mw0000123482|title=Orange - Al Stewart &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''Orange''''' is the fourth studio album by [[Al Stewart]], originally released in 1972, and re-released in 1996 and 2007 on [[Compact Disc|CD]]. Generally regarded as a 'transitional album' between the confessional folk sounds of his first three albums and the historically themed albums of his more successful mid-1970s period, the album includes [[Rick Wakeman]] on piano as well as future [[Elvis Costello and the Attractions]] bassist [[Bruce Thomas]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Al Stewart except where noted.\n\n===Original LP release===\n#\"You Don't Even Know Me\" \u2013 4:00\n#\"Amsterdam\" \u2013 2:56\n#\"Songs Out of Clay\" \u2013 4:16\n#\"The News from Spain\" \u2013 6:34\n#\"[[I Don't Believe You (She Acts Like We Never Have Met)|I Don't Believe You]]\" ([[Bob Dylan]]) \u2013 3:38\n#\"Once an Orange, Always an Orange\" \u2013 4:18\n#\"I'm Falling\" \u2013 4:28\n#\"Night of the 4th of May\" \u2013 6:27\n\n===2007 Collector's Choice Music bonus tracks===\n* \"Soho\" \u2013 3:57\n* \"Elvaston Place\" \u2013 2:52\n* \"It Doesn't Matter Anymore\" ([[Paul Anka]]) \u2013 2:25\n\n==Personnel==\n*Al Stewart \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Tim Renwick]] \u2013 electric guitar (all tracks), Spanish guitar (3)\n*[[Rick Wakeman]] \u2013 piano, organ<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=60Jde3l7WNwC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&source=bl&ots=x7VkxtOZZi&sig=ACfU3U2Bsz5-0CEaIQLerWtddmzQ-WLR3w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiLo4qQ-rDmAhWTGs0KHZZtCGA4MhDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Orange+(Al+Stewart+album)+1972&f=false|title=Legends of Rock Guitar: The Essential Reference of Rock's Greatest Guitarists|first1=Pete|last1=Prown|first2=Harvey P.|last2=Newquist|date=12 December 1997|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n*Bruce Thomas / Brian Odgers \u2013 bass\n*Graham Hunt / Roger Pope / John Wilson \u2013 drums\n*[[Bob Andrews (keyboardist)|Bob Andrews]] \u2013 organ (8)\n*Cal Batchelor \u2013 Spanish guitar (3)\n*Tim Walker \u2013 Spanish guitar (4)\n*John Donnelly, Kevin Powers, Mick Welton \u2013 backing vocals (2)\n*Brinsley Schwarz \u2013 12-string acoustic guitar\n*[[David Hentschel]] \u2013 engineer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Al Stewart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orange (Al Stewart Album)}}\n[[Category:1972 albums]]\n[[Category:Al Stewart albums]]\n[[Category:CBS Records albums]]\n[[Category:Collectors' Choice Music albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Anthony (record producer)]]\n[[Category:albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n\n{{1970s-rock-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Asa-cascadian", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to Brinsley Schwarz (musician) page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_(Al_Stewart_album)"}
{"title_page": "Scottish National Party", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish political party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use Scottish English |date=August 2013 }}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Scottish National Party\n| logo = [[File:Scottish National Party logo 2016.svg|200px]]\n| colorcode = {{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\n| foundation = 7 April 1934\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Scottish nationalism]]\u200c<ref>{{Citation |first=Gerry |last=Hassan |title=The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |year=2009 |pages=5, 9}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvie2004\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Harvie|title=Scotland and Nationalism: Scottish Society and Politics, 1707 to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=80Mx_YSrGv8C|year=2004|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-32724-4|access-date=25 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424053916/https://books.google.com/books?id=80Mx_YSrGv8C|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><br />[[Scottish independence]]<ref>[https://www.snp.org/independence Independence]. ''Scottish National Party.''  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828232112/https://www.snp.org/independence |date=28 August 2017 }}</ref><br />[[Civic nationalism]]<ref>{{Citation |first1=James |last1=Mitchell |first2=Lynn |last2=Bennie |first3=Rob |last3=Johns |title=The Scottish National Party: Transition to Power |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2012 |pages=107\u2013116}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |first=Michael |last=Keating |title=Nationalist Movements in Comparative Perspective |work=The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |year=2009 |pages=214\u2013217}}</ref><br />[[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<ref name=\"Schrijver2006\">{{cite book |author=Frans Schrijver |title=Regionalism After Regionalisation: Spain, France and the United Kingdom |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u8gZklxHTMUC&pg=PA261 |year